---

<section id="about" class="py-24 border-t border-border">
  <div class="container max-w-[1100px] mx-auto px-6">
    <div class="relative rounded-xl border border-primary/20 bg-card/60 px-10 py-14 md:px-16 md:py-20 overflow-hidden">
      <!-- subtle glow -->
      <div class="pointer-events-none absolute -top-1/2 -left-1/4 w-[500px] h-[500px] rounded-full bg-primary/[0.05] blur-[100px]" aria-hidden="true"></div>
      <!-- top accent line -->
      <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 right-0 h-px bg-gradient-to-r from-primary/50 via-primary/20 to-transparent"></div>

      <div class="relative z-10 max-w-[720px]">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-[3px] uppercase text-primary mb-4">About</p>
        <h2 class="text-[clamp(28px,4vw,42px)] font-bold leading-tight text-foreground mb-8">Who I am</h2>

        <div class="space-y-5 text-base text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            I'm <span class="text-foreground font-semibold">Juan Valencia</span>, a Systems Engineering student at 70% of my degree, software developer, and operations senior specialist at Alo Distribution Center.
          </p>
          <p>
            I work where code meets physical reality — where an algorithm isn't just a function, but a picking route, a sorting rule, a decision made a thousand times a day by people and machines alike. That intersection is where I live.
          </p>

          <!-- Bateson blockquote -->
          <blockquote class="relative my-10 pl-8 border-l-2 border-primary">
            <span class="pointer-events-none absolute -top-6 -left-1 text-[88px] leading-none text-primary/15 font-serif select-none" aria-hidden="true">"</span>
            <p class="text-[clamp(18px,2.5vw,24px)] font-semibold text-primary leading-snug">
              Information is a difference that makes a difference.
            </p>
            <footer class="mt-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground">— Gregory Bateson</footer>
          </blockquote>

          <p>
            Not all data matters. Not all processes scale. Not all decisions compound. The skill — whether you're writing software, designing a workflow, or leading a team — is learning to tell the difference.
          </p>
          <p>
            I'm building toward a career that doesn't choose between technology and operations. I believe the best systems thinkers are the ones who've seen both sides of the screen.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
